Jim Clark raced in 63 races.

713
00:40:47,829 --> 00:40:49,079
Some of these cars
look similar,

714
00:40:49,165 --> 00:40:50,666
but they are all
completely different.

715
00:40:50,829 --> 00:40:53,824
In a car like this, he'd do
Formula One Championship.

716
00:40:53,909 --> 00:40:56,224
He raced in the British
Formula Two Championship,

717
00:40:56,309 --> 00:40:59,624
and the French Formula Two
Championship in this car.

718
00:40:59,709 --> 00:41:01,424
He raced in
the Tasman Series,

719
00:41:01,509 --> 00:41:05,144
a sort of Australian Grand Prix
for Down Under, in this car.

720
00:41:05,229 --> 00:41:07,064
And then
there's this Lotus Cortina,

721
00:41:07,149 --> 00:41:09,744
in which he decided
to race in touring cars.

722
00:41:09,829 --> 00:41:11,904
And then if all that
wasn't enough,

723
00:41:11,989 --> 00:41:15,559
he decided to go for
the Indy 500.

724
00:41:17,189 --> 00:41:22,464
First up was the Tasman
Series in Australasia.

725
00:41:22,549 --> 00:41:23,904
Out of the 15 races,

726
00:41:23,989 --> 00:41:27,744
Clark won 11
and took the crown.

727
00:41:27,836 --> 00:41:30,779
Then it was back to
Europe for the British

728
00:41:30,865 --> 00:41:33,759
and French Formula
Two Championships,

729
00:41:34,296 --> 00:41:36,381
both of which he won.

730
00:41:36,549 --> 00:41:38,999
Jim Clark led from the start.

731
00:41:39,389 --> 00:41:41,344
Winner is Jim Clark.

732
00:41:41,429 --> 00:41:43,664
And in between the F2 races,

733
00:41:43,749 --> 00:41:46,064
he was jumping into
his Lotus Cortina

734
00:41:46,149 --> 00:41:49,199
and racking up
touring car victories.

735
00:41:50,109 --> 00:41:51,944
And, on top of all that,

736
00:41:52,029 --> 00:41:53,999
there was America.

737
00:41:57,949 --> 00:41:59,304
The Indianapolis 500

738
00:41:59,389 --> 00:42:00,424
has been called
the greatest

739
00:42:00,509 --> 00:42:02,464
spectacle in racing.

740
00:42:03,789 --> 00:42:06,064
America's
most prestigious race

741
00:42:06,149 --> 00:42:08,384
would be a tough challenge.

742
00:42:08,469 --> 00:42:12,064
Oval racing at higher average
speeds than he was used to

743
00:42:12,149 --> 00:42:14,719
against seasoned
Indy veterans.

744
00:42:17,109 --> 00:42:18,744
For the Indy 500,

745
00:42:18,829 --> 00:42:20,544
Clark raced a specially
developed Lotus

746
00:42:20,629 --> 00:42:23,984
producing just shy
of 500 horsepower.

747
00:42:24,069 --> 00:42:26,464
However,
although he already had

748
00:42:26,549 --> 00:42:29,024
a Formula One
world title to his name,

749
00:42:29,109 --> 00:42:33,424
the Scotsman's CV cut no ice
with the sniffy Indy officials

750
00:42:33,509 --> 00:42:36,384
who made the upstart
from across the pond

751
00:42:36,469 --> 00:42:39,824
take a rookie driving test
before he could compete.

752
00:42:43,069 --> 00:42:45,224
Come Indy weekend,

753
00:42:45,309 --> 00:42:47,264
the upstart
from across the pond

754
00:42:47,349 --> 00:42:50,119
qualified on the front row.

755
00:42:50,949 --> 00:42:52,824
And then...

756
00:42:52,909 --> 00:42:55,984
in the race itself...

757
00:42:56,069 --> 00:42:59,904
Clark, up against
America's finest oval racers,

758
00:42:59,989 --> 00:43:04,319
won by just over two minutes.

759
00:43:10,869 --> 00:43:14,944
Jim Clark, first European
to win at Indianapolis since 1916,

760
00:43:15,029 --> 00:43:19,744
set a new record
of 150.686 miles per hour.

761
00:43:19,829 --> 00:43:23,544
So, what was it
that made Clark so good?

762
00:43:23,629 --> 00:43:29,399
What was it that made him capable
of winning in any type of car?

763
00:43:30,349 --> 00:43:33,304
Jimmy was an absolute
natural driver,

764
00:43:33,389 --> 00:43:35,024
and he did it
without thinking.

765
00:43:35,109 --> 00:43:37,224
He didn't know
why he was driving

766
00:43:37,309 --> 00:43:39,264
in this style the way he did.

767
00:43:43,229 --> 00:43:44,784
In the period
that we're talking about,

768
00:43:44,869 --> 00:43:48,104
we had one and a half-litre
cars, 200 horsepower.

769
00:43:48,189 --> 00:43:52,024
If you drove the car too hard
you would scrub the speed off

770
00:43:52,109 --> 00:43:54,944
and if you lose
a bit of speed,

771
00:43:55,029 --> 00:43:57,024
it's very difficult to
actually make it up again.

772
00:43:57,109 --> 00:43:58,664
And that's what Jimmy had,

773
00:43:58,749 --> 00:44:01,944
the knack of keeping the
momentum of the car going.

774
00:44:02,029 --> 00:44:04,864
I don't think that any
of the modern drivers

775
00:44:04,949 --> 00:44:09,864
could have driven the car anywhere
near as quickly as Jimmy did,

776
00:44:09,949 --> 00:44:12,639
because he was
just so precise.

777
00:44:16,789 --> 00:44:21,904
Besides a supernatural
ability to coax speed out of the car,

778
00:44:21,989 --> 00:44:25,784
Clark also possessed
another vital skill.

779
00:44:25,869 --> 00:44:27,784
A lot of
very good racing drivers

780
00:44:27,869 --> 00:44:29,784
died in Lotuses,

781
00:44:29,869 --> 00:44:33,824
because the Lotus
was a very fragile car.

782
00:44:33,909 --> 00:44:37,224
But Jim Clark was so smooth

783
00:44:37,309 --> 00:44:40,024
that he never put
too much stress

784
00:44:40,109 --> 00:44:43,144
on the areas of a car
that would give up.

785
00:44:43,229 --> 00:44:46,544
In Barcelona, in practice...

786
00:44:46,629 --> 00:44:48,424
he came in after ten laps.

787
00:44:48,509 --> 00:44:50,144
We'd done ten. He said,

788
00:44:50,229 --> 00:44:51,824
"There's something
on the left rear."

789
00:44:51,909 --> 00:44:53,584
Something, something.

790
00:44:53,669 --> 00:44:56,664
"I can feel something on the left rear.
It's... it's not right."

791
00:44:56,749 --> 00:44:58,904
We looked over,
we checked everything.

792
00:44:58,989 --> 00:45:00,664
Everything felt good.

793
00:45:00,749 --> 00:45:02,544
He said, "No, there's
something wrong."

794
00:45:02,629 --> 00:45:08,064
So, that night I took the left
rear suspension to pieces,

795
00:45:08,149 --> 00:45:10,784
and lo and behold
one of the wheel bearings

796
00:45:10,869 --> 00:45:14,184
has just started to wear.

797
00:45:14,269 --> 00:45:17,944
I don't know how anybody could
ever feel that. But he did.

798
00:45:18,029 --> 00:45:21,184
After the race,
when you stripped his car down,

799
00:45:21,269 --> 00:45:24,384
and you stripped
his co-driver's car down,

800
00:45:24,469 --> 00:45:26,264
you could always tell
which parts

801
00:45:26,349 --> 00:45:27,944
came off Jimmy's car

802
00:45:28,029 --> 00:45:29,264
and which parts came off

803
00:45:29,349 --> 00:45:30,864
the other driver's car.

804
00:45:30,949 --> 00:45:33,764
Because the parts
off Jimmy's car

805
00:45:33,849 --> 00:45:36,399
were more or less pristine.

806
00:45:37,549 --> 00:45:39,444
But don't think for a minute

807
00:45:39,529 --> 00:45:41,304
that Clark
was one of those drivers

808
00:45:41,389 --> 00:45:44,959
that could only win
in a perfect car.

809
00:45:46,109 --> 00:45:48,424
One year at Spa, for example,

810
00:45:48,509 --> 00:45:52,839
he was leading the race when
his gearbox started to let go.

811
00:45:54,469 --> 00:45:56,424
Did he give up? Nope.

812
00:45:56,509 --> 00:45:58,504
Instead, he drove
the rest of the race,

813
00:45:58,589 --> 00:46:02,544
and we're talking 160 miles
an hour in the wet...

814
00:46:02,629 --> 00:46:04,464
with one hand
on the steering wheel

815
00:46:04,549 --> 00:46:08,239
and the other holding
the gear lever in place.

816
00:46:13,869 --> 00:46:15,879
And he still won.

817
00:46:17,869 --> 00:46:20,599
By nearly five minutes.

818
00:46:36,389 --> 00:46:39,584
As the 1965 season rolled on,

819
00:46:39,669 --> 00:46:42,864
Clark, having won both
Formula Two championships,

820
00:46:42,949 --> 00:46:45,664
the Tasman Series,

821
00:46:45,749 --> 00:46:47,624
and the Indy 500,

822
00:46:47,709 --> 00:46:51,704
now faced
one remaining challenge.

823
00:46:51,789 --> 00:46:55,184
The biggest challenge,
the Formula One world title.

824
00:46:59,909 --> 00:47:02,424
For the F1 races,
Clark would be driving

825
00:47:02,509 --> 00:47:05,224
a modified version
of the Lotus 25 -

826
00:47:05,309 --> 00:47:06,904
the car that had taken him

827
00:47:06,989 --> 00:47:09,959
to the World Championship
two years earlier.

828
00:47:11,829 --> 00:47:15,064
But as amazing as the 25 was,

829
00:47:15,149 --> 00:47:17,064
there was no
getting round the fact

830
00:47:17,149 --> 00:47:21,664
that by 1965 it was
a three-year-old design,

831
00:47:21,749 --> 00:47:25,664
and the updated version
only had minor changes.

832
00:47:25,749 --> 00:47:27,919
So how would Jim cope?

833
00:47:31,229 --> 00:47:34,704
At the season's
opening race in South Africa,

834
00:47:34,789 --> 00:47:36,224
up against such legends

835
00:47:36,309 --> 00:47:38,584
as Jack Brabham, Graham Hill,

836
00:47:38,669 --> 00:47:42,824
and reigning World Champion
John Surtees...

837
00:47:42,909 --> 00:47:45,984
Clark won
by half a minute,

838
00:47:46,069 --> 00:47:50,759
and did so while suffering
from a slipped disc.

839
00:47:51,989 --> 00:47:54,064
Next up was Spa,

840
00:47:54,149 --> 00:47:56,584
and then
the French Grand Prix:

841
00:47:56,669 --> 00:48:00,904
both of which he also won.

842
00:48:00,989 --> 00:48:03,704
His Lotus may be
a car with an old engine,

843
00:48:03,789 --> 00:48:05,504
but as far as the
opposition are concerned,

844
00:48:05,589 --> 00:48:08,544
it is just
out-distancing all.

845
00:48:08,629 --> 00:48:12,559
Behind the wheel,
Clark was becoming untouchable.

846
00:48:14,829 --> 00:48:17,544
Jimmy would go out beginning
of the practice session

847
00:48:17,629 --> 00:48:20,384
and do
a very, very quick lap.

848
00:48:20,469 --> 00:48:22,504
And come back,
sit on the wall.

849
00:48:22,589 --> 00:48:25,144
You know, there's no point
in wearing the car out.

850
00:48:25,229 --> 00:48:27,824
And then wait and see
what everybody else has done,

851
00:48:27,909 --> 00:48:29,839
and go out and blitz it.

852
00:48:31,549 --> 00:48:33,144
If he wasn't
on pole position,

853
00:48:33,229 --> 00:48:35,264
there was a problem
with the car.

854
00:48:35,349 --> 00:48:37,144
Next up was Silverstone.

855
00:48:37,229 --> 00:48:40,424
And here, it looked like
business as usual

856
00:48:40,509 --> 00:48:43,744
with Clark
leading the pack.

857
00:48:43,829 --> 00:48:46,664
However,
in the closing stages,

858
00:48:46,749 --> 00:48:50,004
his engine was starting
to lose oil pressure

859
00:48:50,089 --> 00:48:54,304
and was in danger of detonating
under cornering G-forces.

860
00:48:54,389 --> 00:48:57,464
While Clark is driving
with no oil pressure on his gauge,

861
00:48:57,549 --> 00:48:59,344
Hill, storming up behind,
breaks the lap record

862
00:48:59,429 --> 00:49:00,864
in his efforts to pass.

863
00:49:00,949 --> 00:49:03,864
So instead of driving the car
through the corner

864
00:49:03,949 --> 00:49:06,744
he just switched it off,
coasted through the corner.

865
00:49:06,829 --> 00:49:09,304
When he was through the corner,
switched it back on again,

866
00:49:09,389 --> 00:49:12,559
did the rest of the lap -
and he won the race.

867
00:49:15,309 --> 00:49:17,904
Eventually, the F1 circus

868
00:49:17,989 --> 00:49:19,624
arrived at the Nurburgring,

869
00:49:19,709 --> 00:49:22,864
a circuit where Clark
had never won.

870
00:49:22,949 --> 00:49:25,464
For the Flying Scot,
tense moments before the start.

871
00:49:25,549 --> 00:49:26,904
Victory in
the German Grand Prix

872
00:49:26,989 --> 00:49:28,784
and he'd be World Champion.

873
00:49:35,789 --> 00:49:37,264
Leading from pole,

874
00:49:37,349 --> 00:49:40,704
Clark finally broke
his Nurburgring jinx,

875
00:49:40,789 --> 00:49:42,704
winning the race,
and with it

876
00:49:42,789 --> 00:49:46,199
the Formula One
world title.

877
00:49:55,149 --> 00:49:59,224
So, let's just sum up
Clark's season of 1965.

878
00:49:59,309 --> 00:50:01,704
Of the 63 races he contested,

879
00:50:01,789 --> 00:50:04,464
he won
a staggering 31 of them,

880
00:50:04,549 --> 00:50:07,464
and was on the podium
a further eight times.

881
00:50:07,549 --> 00:50:11,024
He was now seen as the greatest
racing driver of all time,

882
00:50:11,109 --> 00:50:13,464
in demand the world over.

883
00:50:13,549 --> 00:50:15,384
Yet this shy Scotsman

884
00:50:15,469 --> 00:50:17,784
chose to mark
the year's achievements

885
00:50:17,869 --> 00:50:21,104
with a modest celebration
at his hometown

886
00:50:21,189 --> 00:50:23,719
back in Scotland.

887
00:50:34,589 --> 00:50:39,264
The next two years by
contrast were a disaster,

888
00:50:39,349 --> 00:50:41,724
with multiple
mechanical failures

889
00:50:41,809 --> 00:50:44,359
denying him
another championship.

890
00:50:51,229 --> 00:50:54,064
However, in 1968,

891
00:50:54,149 --> 00:50:55,944
driving the Lotus 49,

892
00:50:56,029 --> 00:50:58,584
another game-changer
from Colin Chapman,

893
00:50:58,669 --> 00:51:03,064
Clark took the first win of
the year in South Africa

894
00:51:03,149 --> 00:51:06,744
and looked set for
another dominant season.

895
00:51:06,829 --> 00:51:09,584
Congratulations, Jim, this was
an absolutely splendid effort.

896
00:51:09,669 --> 00:51:10,904
OK, thank you very much.

897
00:51:10,989 --> 00:51:13,704
And then, on the weekend
of April the 7th,

898
00:51:13,789 --> 00:51:16,904
Clark had a choice of two
races he could compete in,

899
00:51:16,989 --> 00:51:18,344
one at Brands Hatch,

900
00:51:18,429 --> 00:51:21,624
the other a Formula Two race
at Hockenheim.

901
00:51:21,709 --> 00:51:25,279
Fatefully, he entered
the German race.

902
00:51:30,829 --> 00:51:33,584
April the 7th is a...
is a bad day for me.

903
00:51:33,669 --> 00:51:35,464
He wasn't happy.

904
00:51:35,549 --> 00:51:39,144
It was freezing cold
and damp... misty.

905
00:51:39,229 --> 00:51:42,824
We could not get any heat
into the tyres.

906
00:51:42,909 --> 00:51:46,624
Couldn't get any temperature
in them no matter what we did.

907
00:51:46,709 --> 00:51:48,144
Jimmy said to me
before the race:

908
00:51:48,229 --> 00:51:50,184
"Do not expect
anything from me today.

909
00:51:50,269 --> 00:51:55,839
Just keep me informed with the pit
board where I am, how many laps to go."

910
00:51:57,208 --> 00:51:59,818
That's the last thing
he said.

911
00:52:11,629 --> 00:52:16,544
On lap five, Clark's car
suddenly speared off the track

912
00:52:16,629 --> 00:52:19,719
at 170 miles an hour.

913
00:52:23,073 --> 00:52:26,188
I got to the scene, and they took me
through the undergrowth to this...

914
00:52:26,274 --> 00:52:29,629
There's no Armco.
There's Tarmac, trees.

915
00:52:29,744 --> 00:52:30,899
Literally.

916
00:52:31,149 --> 00:52:32,804
And the sheer path.

917
00:52:32,889 --> 00:52:36,679
And I just saw
what was left of a car... Oh.

918
00:52:39,549 --> 00:52:41,384
There was nothing to see.

919
00:52:41,469 --> 00:52:43,984
I said, "Where's the engine
gearbox? What's going on?"

920
00:52:44,069 --> 00:52:46,224
What's happened?"
They said, "That's..."

921
00:52:46,309 --> 00:52:50,384
It was about 35 yards away
through the saplings.

922
00:52:50,469 --> 00:52:52,544
It just cut
the saplings down.

923
00:52:52,629 --> 00:52:56,599
And I said, "Where's, where's the driver?
Where's Jimmy?" They said, "No."

924
00:52:58,337 --> 00:53:01,907
When you've just... lost...

925
00:53:02,709 --> 00:53:04,464
the best driver
in the world,

926
00:53:04,549 --> 00:53:06,396
what the hell do you do?

927
00:53:07,949 --> 00:53:09,984
Jim Clark, he's a god.

928
00:53:10,069 --> 00:53:12,344
And the first time I saw him,
my God, it's...

929
00:53:12,429 --> 00:53:15,224
I can't believe it. And you're
actually talking to him.

930
00:53:15,309 --> 00:53:17,624
It was awe-inspiring.

931
00:53:17,709 --> 00:53:20,839
Life is worth living.

932
00:53:22,869 --> 00:53:24,896
It's...

933
00:53:25,309 --> 00:53:28,119
for me, it's tearful.

934
00:53:29,189 --> 00:53:31,149
I'm sorry.

935
00:53:35,029 --> 00:53:37,424
According
to the medical report,

936
00:53:37,509 --> 00:53:40,584
Clark died instantly
of a broken neck

937
00:53:40,669 --> 00:53:44,984
and the crash was later
put down to a deflating tyre.

938
00:53:45,069 --> 00:53:48,704
When he died, he was just 32.

939
00:53:48,789 --> 00:53:54,879
But in his short career he had racked
up some truly incredible achievements.

940
00:53:55,721 --> 00:53:59,796
In Formula One,
he won 25 of his 73 races,

941
00:53:59,920 --> 00:54:03,826
which in percentage terms puts
him way ahead of Hamilton, Vettel,

942
00:54:03,912 --> 00:54:05,227
and even Schumacher.

943
00:54:05,313 --> 00:54:07,308
In pole positions, he had 33.

944
00:54:07,394 --> 00:54:08,949
Which again,
in percentage terms,

945
00:54:09,149 --> 00:54:11,584
makes him
second best of all time,

946
00:54:11,669 --> 00:54:13,944
just behind Fangio.

947
00:54:14,029 --> 00:54:15,504
Then there are
the Grand Slams:

948
00:54:15,589 --> 00:54:19,144
that's where a driver gets
pole position, fastest lap,

949
00:54:19,229 --> 00:54:22,504
the win and leads
every lap of the race.

950
00:54:22,589 --> 00:54:25,544
Schumacher has five
Grand Slams to his name.

951
00:54:25,629 --> 00:54:27,184
Senna, four.

952
00:54:27,269 --> 00:54:29,624
Jim Clark, eight.

953
00:54:29,709 --> 00:54:33,039
That's more than
any other driver in history.

954
00:54:34,829 --> 00:54:37,904
You might imagine
that a man with such skills

955
00:54:37,989 --> 00:54:40,744
would be rated highly
by other drivers.

956
00:54:40,829 --> 00:54:43,304
And you'd be right.

957
00:54:43,389 --> 00:54:46,344
I was invited to
a cocktail party for Fangio,

958
00:54:46,429 --> 00:54:49,744
and he said to me,
"In my opinion,

959
00:54:49,829 --> 00:54:53,064
Jimmy Clark was the
greatest racing driver ever."

960
00:54:53,149 --> 00:54:55,104
And coming from Fangio,

961
00:54:55,189 --> 00:54:58,264
there's no better
compliment than that.

962
00:54:58,349 --> 00:55:00,464
And the five-time
World Champion

963
00:55:00,549 --> 00:55:02,664
was not the only
South American

964
00:55:02,749 --> 00:55:05,279
who idolised the Scotsman.

965
00:55:06,589 --> 00:55:08,784
At Clark's old school
in Edinburgh,

966
00:55:08,869 --> 00:55:12,704
there's a plaque commemorating
his achievements.

967
00:55:12,789 --> 00:55:16,384
And in 1991,
the reigning World Champion

968
00:55:16,469 --> 00:55:19,264
made a special pilgrimage
to the school

969
00:55:19,349 --> 00:55:23,024
to pay his respects.

970
00:55:23,109 --> 00:55:27,424
Of Clark, Senna said simply,
"He was my boyhood hero.

971
00:55:27,509 --> 00:55:30,744
He was the best of the best."

972
00:55:30,829 --> 00:55:34,104
And like Senna, Clark died
when he was driving

973
00:55:34,189 --> 00:55:36,389
at his absolute peak.

974
00:55:36,537 --> 00:55:39,784
Like Senna, who knows
how many more races

975
00:55:39,869 --> 00:55:43,239
and championships
he could have racked up?

976
00:55:47,827 --> 00:55:52,622
He was the benchmark.
That was it.

977
00:55:52,754 --> 00:55:57,069
Most of what I was able to do
in motor racing was done...

978
00:55:57,232 --> 00:56:00,027
by the manner in
which Jim Clark drove,

979
00:56:00,269 --> 00:56:02,719
and... I just followed him.

980
00:56:03,448 --> 00:56:05,163
He was a gentleman.

981
00:56:05,787 --> 00:56:08,818
He was a gentleman,
and a gentle man.

982
00:56:09,269 --> 00:56:11,759
It's a pity he's not
around now, because...

983
00:56:13,545 --> 00:56:15,719
it'd be nice to have him.

984
00:56:23,509 --> 00:56:25,784
He was
an amazing man.

985
00:56:25,869 --> 00:56:29,068
- Just incredible.
- All of that's amazing.

986
00:56:29,154 --> 00:56:30,344
Yeah.

987
00:56:30,429 --> 00:56:32,144
What I find truly amazing

988
00:56:32,229 --> 00:56:35,131
is how many championships
he took part in.

989
00:56:35,217 --> 00:56:37,784
I mean, can you imagine
Lewis Hamilton

990
00:56:37,869 --> 00:56:39,712
getting out of his
Formula One car and saying,

991
00:56:39,798 --> 00:56:41,024
"I haven't got time
for any interviews,

992
00:56:41,109 --> 00:56:43,009
cos I've got to go and
do a touring car race."

993
00:56:43,095 --> 00:56:44,504
- Just wouldn't.
- And he did.

994
00:56:44,589 --> 00:56:46,915
The other thing worth remembering
is back in the early '60s,

995
00:56:47,001 --> 00:56:50,756
if you went to Australia, if you flew
to Australia that meant eight stops.

996
00:56:50,842 --> 00:56:53,631
And there were no flat beds.
There weren't even any movies.

997
00:56:53,717 --> 00:56:56,564
And let's not forget
he'd get off that aeroplane,

998
00:56:56,649 --> 00:56:58,504
do a race, win it -
obviously,

999
00:56:58,589 --> 00:57:01,162
then get on another aeroplane
straight away to France

1000
00:57:01,248 --> 00:57:03,865
- to win a race there.
- No, it is astonishing.

1001
00:57:03,951 --> 00:57:05,951
I mean, everybody has
a favourite racing driver.

1002
00:57:06,037 --> 00:57:08,146
I'm sure everybody here
does as well.

1003
00:57:08,232 --> 00:57:10,224
It's, you know, it's the
Senna, Schumacher,

1004
00:57:10,309 --> 00:57:12,184
Villeneuve,
Romain Grosjean...

1005
00:57:12,269 --> 00:57:14,464
Fangio.

1006
00:57:14,549 --> 00:57:18,184
But if you use maths to
measure a driver's greatness,

1007
00:57:18,269 --> 00:57:22,124
you have to conclude
it was Jim Clark.

1008
00:57:22,209 --> 00:57:24,146
Good night.

1009
